> eric@ericwichman.com wrote:
> >> The main objective is to do the trip with an EV or another renewable
> >> fuel vehicle. I'd like to do it with an EV, however budget is an
> >> issue. (when is it not?)
>
> Bruce EVangel Parmenter wrote:
> > there will be plenty of affluent cross-country drivers to steal your
> > thunder. You will likely read about them in future newswires I post.
>
> Obviously, you can do anything with enough money. Driving cross country
> when cost is no object is no big deal. No one would notice.
>
> There are also going to be publicity stunts where some company hack
> drives their "breakthrough" across the country, and loudly proclaims it
> "the world's first..." The clueless media will probably believe the
> hype, and never bother to fact-check it. Hopefully, they will be ignored
> as well.
>
> >> Conversion is ok as long as it's reliable. A manufactured American
> >> made vehicle would be ideal.
>
> William McKemie wrote:
> > 1) A conversion may not be reliable until it has been shaken out
> > for a year or two.
> > 2) The bigger the pack you have, the fewer "fuel" stops you will
> > need.
> > 3) Your best charging resource is RV parks.
>
> Excellent points!
>
> This discussion reminds me of conversations I had with EV pioneer Bob
> Rice (RIP). He participated in the "Great Electric Car Race" in 1968.
> Here's a summary:
>
> "It was one of the finest displays of academic competition ever
> conceived. Two teams of students, one from MIT and one from Caltech,
> raced across the country in conventional cars, converted to run
> exclusively on electric power... Caltech's winning entry was an
> electrified VW Microbus, which crossed the country in 8 days, 19 hours,
> and 46 minutes. Stopping 59 times for battery charges, it averaged 0.3
> miles/KWH and consumed $50 worth of fuel -- a reasonable cost for the
> vehicle's 4700 lbs weight and three passenger payload."
>
> So I'm thinking...
>
> Maybe it's time to do it again? Could we set up a coast-to-coast race,
> where participants have to drive the whole distance on electricity? Set
> up the rules to encourage innovation and economy; not big budgets and
> unobtainable technology. Something to get students interested.
>
> No big cash prizes (so it won't attract the "buy the race" types). But
> recognition, certificates, trophies, etc. Maybe something like a "3000
> mile club", where there can be any number of winners, just by going 3000
> miles in the race.
>
> Here's an idea I like: Find a sponsor to subsidize the cost of batteries
> (perhaps a battery manufacturer). The "entry fee" in fact provides you
> with a set of batteries. This way, everyone has the same batteries, to
> keep things fair. Make the entry fee something affordable like $1000 --
> that's enough for a dozen golf cart batteries, though something better
> could be supplied with sponsorship.
>
> Everything else is chosen by the individual team. They can pick their
> donor car, motor, controller, and everything else. The rules for the
> race can even allow them to add other batteries, as long as the ones
> provided are *also* in the vehicle.
>
> Or... Ham radio has awards like DXCC (Distance eXtreme Century Club --
> talked to hams in 100 countries) and WAC (Worked All Counties in the
> USA). They are honorary awards, where participants keep their own
> records, and only need to submit proof if there is question. So perhaps
> we could have an EV "race" where participants drive their EV to as many
> states as possible. Who can get the first "50 state" EV? :-)
> --
> Don't worry about people stealing your ideas. If your ideas are any
> good, you'll have to ram them down people's throats. -- Howard Aiken
> --
> Lee A. Hart http://www.sunrise-ev.com/LeesEVs leeahart@earthlink.net
